  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">&#x2018;Hanyoyin kariya ga uwa&#x2019; (Safe motherhood)</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Though Nigeria has only 2.5% of the world&apos;s population, it has over 10% of the world&apos;s maternal and child deaths. Some of the causes of maternal deaths relate to limited access to health care and poor health systems. Through health education, PADEAP is creating awareness of and demand for maternal health services. They&apos;re advocating for policy changes so that maternity care becomes free, including emergency obstetric care for women who experience birth complications. Traditional birth attendants support pregnant women in communities and play a role in referring women to health facilities to deliver their babies. As a result of the project, more women are using antenatal care services and receiving the support of skilled health providers, as well as learning about family planning methods. Campaigning work will result in the passage of a health bill and increased local government funding, so that maternal and child health services are free. In addition to the project grant, PADEAP have been awarded &#xA3;40,000 to strengthen their capacity and more effectively support their partners in Africa.</narrative>
  </description>
